# James Gay‑Rees  

*British film producer*  

**Occupation** [Film producer](/Film_producer) Years&#160;active 1991–present  

James Gay‑Rees is a British [film producer](/Film_producer) whose résumé reads like a catalogue of critically‑acclaimed documentaries that have, against all odds, managed to stay awake long enough to win awards. He has spent the last three decades shepherding stories about sports legends, racing drivers, and other assorted cultural curiosities through the often‑mundane gauntlet of cinema, leaving a trail of glittering trophies and the occasional Oscar‑shaped breadcrumb in his wake.  

Born somewhere between the mist‑shrouded banks of the River Test and the more temperate climes of a university dormitory, Gay‑Rees cultivated an early fascination with the moving image that was somewhere between a genuine passion and a strategic escape from the tedium of suburban life. He eventually found himself at the [University of Southampton](/University_of_Southampton), where he allegedly “studied” something that could be loosely described as media theory, though his professors were more interested in his habit of quoting obscure 1970s punk lyrics during seminars.  

After graduation he made a brief, ill‑fated pilgrimage to London where he found employment with [Miramax](/Miramax) — a stint that lasted long enough to learn the art of corporate politeness without actually believing in it. A year later he decamped to New York, then to Los Angeles, where he took up a position as head of development at the modestly named Orbit Productions. It was there that he discovered his true calling: turning painstakingly researched documentaries into products that could actually sell tickets, or at least streaming numbers.  

His first foray into the documentary arena was the 2010 film **[Exit Through the Gift Shop](/Exit_Through_the_Gift_Shop)**, a meta‑experiment that earned him a nomination for the [Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature](/Academy_Award_for_Best_Documentary_Feature). The film’s title, a reference to a famous street‑art stunt, was as pretentious as it was clever, and it set the tone for a career defined by ambitious projects that masquerade as “just another documentary” while secretly aiming for cultural immortality.  

His sophomore effort, **[Senna](/Senna_(film))** (2010), proved that he could actually make a documentary that people would *watch* rather than just *pretend* to watch for the sake of pretension. The film not only secured a [BAFTA Award for Best Documentary](/BAFTA_Award_for_Best_Documentary) but also cemented his reputation as the sort of producer who could make a Formula 1 driver’s life feel like a Shakespearean tragedy — if Shakespeare had been a fan of high‑speed aerodynamics.  

In 2015 he produced **[Amy](/Amy_(2015_film))**, a portrait of the ill‑fated singer Amy Winehouse that earned him a slew of awards, including the [Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature](/Academy_Award_for_Best_Documentary_Feature) at the 88th Academy Awards. The film’s raw, unflinching look at a star’s self‑destruction was so compelling that it briefly made the world forget that it was, in fact, a documentary and not a cautionary tale about the perils of fame.  

